I'll see to it right away.

464
00:36:46,464 --> 00:36:49,661
Try one of theseJamaican cigars,
Ambassador. They're good.

465
00:36:49,734 --> 00:36:53,193
Thank you, no. I do not support the work
of imperialist stooges.

466
00:36:53,272 --> 00:36:55,866
Oh, only Commie stooges, huh?

467
00:36:55,941 --> 00:36:57,499
Mr. President.

468
00:36:59,379 --> 00:37:02,678
You're gonna let that lousy Commie punk
vomit all over us like this?

469
00:37:02,749 --> 00:37:03,841
Mr. President?

470
00:37:03,917 --> 00:37:07,684
They haven't reached Premier Kissoff.
They don't know where he is...

471
00:37:07,755 --> 00:37:10,155
and he won't be back for two hours.

472
00:37:11,225 --> 00:37:13,717
Try B-8-6-5-4-3 Moscow.

473
00:37:13,795 --> 00:37:15,888
You would never have found him
through his office.

474
00:37:15,964 --> 00:37:19,992
Our premier is a man of the people,
but he is also a man, if you follow.

475
00:37:20,069 --> 00:37:22,765
- Degenerate atheistic Commie.
- What did you say?

476
00:37:22,839 --> 00:37:26,401
I said Premier Kissoff is
a degenerate atheistic Commie!

477
00:37:26,477 --> 00:37:29,412
- Have this ignorant fool...
- I'm sorry!

478
00:37:29,480 --> 00:37:33,416
Mr. President,
I think they're trying the number.

479
00:37:44,063 --> 00:37:47,191
Gentlemen, you can't fight in here.
This is the War Room!

480
00:37:47,266 --> 00:37:50,100
What is going on here?
I demand an explanation.

481
00:37:50,170 --> 00:37:54,436
This clumsy fool tried to plant
that ridiculous camera on me.

482
00:37:54,508 --> 00:37:57,103
You bet your sweets, Mr. Commie!
Look at this, Mr. President.

483
00:37:57,178 --> 00:38:00,773
This lousy Commie rat was taking
pictures with this of the big board!

484
00:38:01,849 --> 00:38:03,715
Mr. Ambassador!

485
00:38:03,785 --> 00:38:08,051
This clumsy fool attempted to plant
that ridiculous camera on me.

486
00:38:08,123 --> 00:38:10,991
That's a damn lie!
I saw him with my own eyes.

487
00:38:11,060 --> 00:38:15,258
This is outrageous. I have never heard
of such behavior in the War Room before.

488
00:38:15,331 --> 00:38:17,823
Mr. President, I think
they're getting him on the line.

489
00:38:45,833 --> 00:38:47,767
You got to hand it to those Commies.

490
00:38:47,835 --> 00:38:52,363
Yeah. Those trucks sure look like
the real thing, don't they?

491
00:38:52,441 --> 00:38:54,375
I wonder where they got them from.

492
00:38:54,443 --> 00:38:56,707
Probably bought them
from the army as war surplus.

493
00:39:00,417 --> 00:39:04,478
Okay, open up at 200 yards.

494
00:40:01,719 --> 00:40:05,383
Tell him where you are and that
you'll speak if I say anything untrue...

495
00:40:05,457 --> 00:40:07,755
but nothing more than that.

496
00:40:09,361 --> 00:40:12,763
Alexi? Alexi, please.
I beg you.

497
00:40:13,833 --> 00:40:16,427
But I don't have a phone.

498
00:40:16,503 --> 00:40:19,064
Give him the phone.

499
00:40:45,869 --> 00:40:50,239
I've done as you asked.
Be careful. I think he is drunk.

500
00:40:53,244 --> 00:40:57,705
Hello? Hello, Dimitri?

501
00:40:57,783 --> 00:41:00,183
Listen, I can't hear too well.

502
00:41:00,252 --> 00:41:03,518
Could you turn the music down
a little?

503
00:41:03,590 --> 00:41:05,524
That's much better.

504
00:41:05,592 --> 00:41:08,220
Yeah. Yeah.

505
00:41:09,497 --> 00:41:12,295
Fine. I can hear you now, Dimitri.

506
00:41:12,366 --> 00:41:15,859
Clear and plain
and coming through fine.

507
00:41:15,938 --> 00:41:20,341
I'm coming through fine, too, eh?
Good.

508
00:41:20,409 --> 00:41:24,369
Well, then, as you say,
we're both coming through fine. Good.

509
00:41:24,447 --> 00:41:26,381
It's good that you're fine...

510
00:41:26,449 --> 00:41:28,713
and I'm fine.

511
00:41:28,785 --> 00:41:32,017
I agree with you.
It's great to be fine.

512
00:41:32,923 --> 00:41:35,118
Now, Dimitri...

513
00:41:35,192 --> 00:41:40,893
you know how we've always talked
about the possibility...

514
00:41:40,966 --> 00:41:43,662
of something going wrong
with the bomb.

515
00:41:45,037 --> 00:41:47,005
The bomb, Dimitri.

516
00:41:48,207 --> 00:41:50,835
The hydrogen bomb.

517
00:41:50,910 --> 00:41:53,880
Well, now, what happened is...

518
00:41:53,947 --> 00:41:58,179
one of our base commanders,
he had a sort of...

519
00:41:58,252 --> 00:42:01,484
Well, he went a little funny
in the head.

520
00:42:01,556 --> 00:42:04,650
You know, just a little funny.

521
00:42:04,726 --> 00:42:08,356
And he went and did a silly thing.

522
00:42:09,431 --> 00:42:11,365
I'll tell you what he did.

523
00:42:11,433 --> 00:42:13,766
He ordered his planes...

524
00:42:15,438 --> 00:42:17,906
to attack your country.

525
00:42:17,974 --> 00:42:20,375
Let me finish, Dimitri.

526
00:42:21,379 --> 00:42:23,347
Let me finish, Dimitri.

527
00:42:23,414 --> 00:42:26,611
Listen, how do you think
I feel about it?

528
00:42:26,684 --> 00:42:29,552
Can you imagine how I feel
about it, Dimitri?

529
00:42:31,089 --> 00:42:33,250
Why do you think I'm calling you?

530
00:42:33,325 --> 00:42:35,351
Just to say hello?

531
00:42:36,429 --> 00:42:38,829
Of course I like to speak to you!

532
00:42:38,898 --> 00:42:41,423
Of course I like to say hello!

533
00:42:41,501 --> 00:42:43,697
Not now, but anytime, Dimitri.

534
00:42:43,771 --> 00:42:47,798
I'm just calling up to tell you
something terrible has happened.

535
00:42:47,875 --> 00:42:50,868
Of course, it's a friendly call.

536
00:42:50,946 --> 00:42:55,212
Listen, if it wasn't friendly,
you probably wouldn't have even got it.

537
00:42:57,520 --> 00:43:02,287
They will not reach their targets
for at least another hour.

538
00:43:02,358 --> 00:43:05,453
I am positive, Dimitri.

539
00:43:05,529 --> 00:43:07,963
I've been all over this
with your ambassador.

540
00:43:08,031 --> 00:43:10,523
It is not a trick.

541
00:43:10,602 --> 00:43:12,069
I'll tell you.

542
00:43:12,136 --> 00:43:15,970
We'd like to give your Air Staff
a complete rundown on the targets...

543
00:43:16,040 --> 00:43:19,306
the flight plans
and defensive systems of the planes.

544
00:43:19,378 --> 00:43:24,315
Yes, if we're unable
to recall the planes...

545
00:43:24,383 --> 00:43:27,046
I'd say, well...

546
00:43:28,455 --> 00:43:32,825
we're just gonna have to help you
destroy them, Dimitri.

547
00:43:32,894 --> 00:43:35,829
I know they're our boys.

548
00:43:35,897 --> 00:43:38,422
Listen. Now, who should we call?

549
00:43:40,269 --> 00:43:44,763
Who should we call?
Sorry, you faded away.

550
00:43:45,974 --> 00:43:49,843
The Peoples Central
Air Defense Headquarters.

551
00:43:49,913 --> 00:43:52,211
Where is that, Dimitri?

552
00:43:52,282 --> 00:43:54,410
In Omsk. Right.

553
00:43:55,486 --> 00:43:56,748
Yes.

554
00:43:56,820 --> 00:43:59,721
You'll call them first, will you?

555
00:44:01,226 --> 00:44:04,161
Do you happen to have the phone number
on you, Dimitri?

556
00:44:06,031 --> 00:44:09,024
What? I see.
Just ask for Omsk information.

557
00:44:11,103 --> 00:44:15,234
I'm sorry too, Dimitri.
I'm very sorry.

558
00:44:15,309 --> 00:44:19,143
All right, you're sorrier than I am.
But I am sorry as well.

559
00:44:21,448 --> 00:44:23,713
I am as sorry as you are, Dimitri.

560
00:44:23,785 --> 00:44:25,753
Don't say that you're more sorry
than I am...

561
00:44:25,820 --> 00:44:28,755
because I'm capable of being
just as sorry as you are.

562
00:44:28,823 --> 00:44:30,758
So we're both sorry, all right?

563
00:44:30,826 --> 00:44:32,259
All right.

564
00:44:33,495 --> 00:44:37,762
Yes, he's right here. Yes, he wants
to talk to you. Just a second.

565
00:44:50,314 --> 00:44:52,010
What?

566
00:45:10,704 --> 00:45:13,572
What? What is it? What?

567
00:45:13,641 --> 00:45:16,667
The fools. The mad fools.

568
00:45:18,079 --> 00:45:20,241
What's happened?

569
00:45:20,316 --> 00:45:22,648
The doomsday machine.

570
00:45:22,718 --> 00:45:25,278
The doomsday machine?
What is that?

571
00:45:25,354 --> 00:45:30,759
A device which will destroy
all human and animal life on Earth.

572
00:45:30,827 --> 00:45:33,091
All human and animal life?

573
00:45:47,946 --> 00:45:50,245
- Mandrake?
- Yes, Jack?

574
00:45:51,551 --> 00:45:55,146
Have you ever seen a Commie
drink a glass of water?

575
00:45:55,221 --> 00:45:59,784
Well, I can't say I have, Jack.

576
00:46:00,995 --> 00:46:05,865
Vodka. That's what they drink,
isn't it? Never water.

577
00:46:05,934 --> 00:46:10,338
I believe that's what they drink, yes.

578
00:46:10,406 --> 00:46:13,864
On no account will a Commie
ever drink water...

579
00:46:13,943 --> 00:46:16,275
and not without good reason.

580
00:46:17,347 --> 00:46:20,009
Oh, yes.

581
00:46:20,084 --> 00:46:25,148
I can't quite see
what you're getting at.

582
00:46:26,291 --> 00:46:29,488
Water. That's what I'm getting at.
Water.

583
00:46:31,029 --> 00:46:34,488
Mandrake, water is the source
of all life.

584
00:46:36,035 --> 00:46:39,631
Seven-tenths of this Earth's surface
is water.

585
00:46:39,706 --> 00:46:43,039
Why, do you realize that...

586
00:46:43,110 --> 00:46:46,171
70% of you is water?

587
00:46:46,247 --> 00:46:47,680
Good Lord.

588
00:46:47,748 --> 00:46:52,880
And as human beings,
you and I need fresh, pure water...

589
00:46:52,955 --> 00:46:56,550
to replenish
our precious bodily fluids.

590
00:46:56,625 --> 00:46:59,355
- You beginning to understand?
- Yes.

591
00:47:06,703 --> 00:47:11,971
Have you never wondered why I drink
only distilled water...

592
00:47:12,042 --> 00:47:16,446
or rainwater,
and only pure grain alcohol?

593
00:47:16,515 --> 00:47:19,814
It did occur to me, Jack, yes.

594
00:47:20,919 --> 00:47:24,879
Have you ever heard of fluoridation
of water?

595
00:47:25,958 --> 00:47:29,793
Yes, I have heard of that, Jack, yes.

596
00:47:29,863 --> 00:47:31,797
Do you know what it is?

597
00:47:31,865 --> 00:47:34,993
No, no, I don't know what it is.

598
00:47:35,068 --> 00:47:39,005
Do you realize that fluoridation...

599
00:47:39,073 --> 00:47:41,906
is the most monstrously conceived...

600
00:47:41,976 --> 00:47:44,775
and dangerous Communist plot
we have ever had to face?

601
00:47:51,188 --> 00:47:53,156
Two can play at that game, soldier.

602
00:47:58,262 --> 00:48:00,992
That's nice shooting, soldier!

603
00:48:25,459 --> 00:48:27,519
Mandrake, come here.

604
00:48:27,596 --> 00:48:29,621
You calling me, Jack?

605
00:48:29,698 --> 00:48:32,132
Come over here
and help me with this belt.

606
00:48:35,171 --> 00:48:38,163
I haven't had very much experience...

607
00:48:38,241 --> 00:48:41,040
with those sort of machines.

608
00:48:41,111 --> 00:48:44,911
I've only ever pressed a button
in my old Spitfire.

609
00:48:44,982 --> 00:48:48,612
In the name of Her Majesty and the
Continental Congress, feed me this belt.

610
00:48:48,686 --> 00:48:53,453
Jack, I'd love to come,
but what's happened, you see...

611
00:48:53,524 --> 00:48:56,323
the string in my leg is gone.

612
00:48:57,396 --> 00:49:01,196
- The what?
- The string. I never told you.

613
00:49:01,267 --> 00:49:05,170
I've got a gammy leg.
Oh, dear. Gone. Shot off.

614
00:49:07,307 --> 00:49:10,971
Mandrake, come over here.
The redcoats are coming.

615
00:49:12,079 --> 00:49:16,244
When it is detonated, it will produce
enough radioactive fallout...

616
00:49:16,318 --> 00:49:18,252
so that in ten months...

617
00:49:18,320 --> 00:49:21,414
the surface of the Earth
will be as dead as the moon!

618
00:49:21,490 --> 00:49:24,460
Come on, De Sadesky!
That's ridiculous!

619
00:49:24,527 --> 00:49:28,657
Our studies show even the worst fallout
is down to a safe level after two weeks.

620
00:49:28,731 --> 00:49:33,760
- You never heard of cobalt theoium G.
- What about it?

621
00:49:33,837 --> 00:49:37,934
Cobalt thorium G has
a radioactive half-life of 93 years.

622
00:49:38,009 --> 00:49:41,103
If you take 50 H bombs
in the 100 megaton range...

623
00:49:41,179 --> 00:49:43,579
and jacket them
with cobalt thorium G...

624
00:49:43,648 --> 00:49:48,279
when they are exploded,
they will produce a doomsday shroud...

625
00:49:48,354 --> 00:49:50,652
a lethal cloud of radioactivity...

626
00:49:50,723 --> 00:49:55,161
which will encircle the Earth
for 93 years!

627
00:49:55,228 --> 00:49:58,789
What a load of Commie bull.
I mean, after all.

628
00:49:59,867 --> 00:50:02,529
I'm afraid I don't understand
something, Alexi.

629
00:50:02,603 --> 00:50:06,232
Is the premier threatening to explode it
if our planes carry out their attack?

630
00:50:06,308 --> 00:50:08,868
No, sir. It is not a thing
a sane man would do.

631
00:50:08,944 --> 00:50:11,879
The doomsday machine is designed
to trigger itself automatically.

632
00:50:11,947 --> 00:50:14,212
Surely you can disarm it somehow.

633
00:50:14,284 --> 00:50:18,220
It is designed to explode if
any attempt is made to un-trigger it.

634
00:50:18,288 --> 00:50:19,550
Automatically?

635
00:50:19,622 --> 00:50:22,217
It's a Commie trick!
We're wasting valuable time!

636
00:50:22,293 --> 00:50:25,387
Look at the big board!
They're getting ready to clobber us!

637
00:50:25,463 --> 00:50:30,128
This is absolute madness.
Why should you build such a thing?

638
00:50:30,202 --> 00:50:32,170
There are those of us
who fought against it.

639
00:50:32,237 --> 00:50:34,296
But in the end, we could not keep up
with the expense involved...

640
00:50:34,373 --> 00:50:38,902
in the arms race, the space race
and the peace race.

641
00:50:38,978 --> 00:50:44,212
At the same time, our people grumbled
for more nylons and washing machines.

642
00:50:44,284 --> 00:50:46,844
Our doomsday scheme cost us
just a small fraction...

643
00:50:46,920 --> 00:50:50,152
of what we have been spending on defense
in a single year.

644
00:50:50,225 --> 00:50:54,662
The deciding factor was when we learned
your country was working similarly...

645
00:50:54,729 --> 00:50:56,664
and we were afraid of a doomsday gap!

646
00:50:56,732 --> 00:51:00,099
This is preposterous! I've never
approved of anything like that.

647
00:51:00,169 --> 00:51:03,002
<i>Our source was The New York Times.</i>

648
00:51:03,072 --> 00:51:06,975
Dr. Strangelove, do we have anything
like that in the works?

649
00:51:07,043 --> 00:51:09,511
A moment, please, Mr. President.

650
00:51:12,250 --> 00:51:15,686
Under the authority granted me...

651
00:51:15,753 --> 00:51:19,918
as director of weapons research
and development...

652
00:51:19,992 --> 00:51:24,190
I commissioned last year
a study of this project...

653
00:51:24,263 --> 00:51:26,494
by the Bland Corporation.

654
00:51:26,566 --> 00:51:29,729
Based on the findings of the report...

655
00:51:29,803 --> 00:51:35,299
my conclusion was that this idea
was not a practical deterrent...

656
00:51:35,376 --> 00:51:39,210
for reasons which at this moment
must be all too obvious.

657
00:51:39,280 --> 00:51:42,682
You mean it is possible for them
to have built such a thing?

658
00:51:46,856 --> 00:51:51,725
Mr. President, the technology required
is easily within the means...

659
00:51:51,794 --> 00:51:56,198
of even the smallest nuclear power.

660
00:51:56,266 --> 00:52:00,225
It requires only the will to do so.

661
00:52:01,239 --> 00:52:05,107
But how is it possible for this thing
to be triggered automatically...

662
00:52:05,176 --> 00:52:07,508
and at the same time
impossible to un-trigger?

663
00:52:07,579 --> 00:52:11,607
Mr. President,
it is not only possible...

664
00:52:11,684 --> 00:52:13,618
it is essential.

665
00:52:13,686 --> 00:52:18,124
That is the whole idea
of this machine, you know.

666
00:52:18,191 --> 00:52:23,391
Deterrence is the art of producing
in the mind of the enemy...

667
00:52:23,464 --> 00:52:26,058
the fear of attack.

668
00:52:26,133 --> 00:52:31,071
And so because of the automated and
irrevocable decision-making process...

669
00:52:31,139 --> 00:52:35,041
which rules out human meddling...

670
00:52:35,110 --> 00:52:39,070
the doomsday machine is terrifying...

671
00:52:39,148 --> 00:52:41,241
and simple to understand...

672
00:52:41,317 --> 00:52:45,015
and completely credible
and convincing.

673
00:52:45,089 --> 00:52:48,422
I wish we had one of them
doomsday machines.

674
00:52:48,492 --> 00:52:52,088
But this is fantastic, Strangelove.
How can it be triggered automatically?

675
00:52:52,163 --> 00:52:55,963
It's remarkably simple to do that.

676
00:52:56,034 --> 00:52:59,562
When you merely wish to bury bombs...

677
00:52:59,639 --> 00:53:01,971
there's no limit to the size.

678
00:53:02,041 --> 00:53:04,271
After that, they are connected...

679
00:53:04,343 --> 00:53:08,371
to a gigantic complex of computers.

680
00:53:08,448 --> 00:53:14,183
Now then, a specific and clearly
defined set of circumstances...

681
00:53:14,255 --> 00:53:17,713
under which the bombs
are to be exploded...

682
00:53:17,792 --> 00:53:21,820
is programmed into a tape memory bank.

683
00:53:21,897 --> 00:53:24,991
Hmm. Strangelove?

684
00:53:26,068 --> 00:53:29,129
What kind of a name is that?
That ain't no Kraut name, is it?

685
00:53:29,205 --> 00:53:31,503
He changed it when he became a citizen.

686
00:53:31,575 --> 00:53:34,568
It used to be Merkwurdichliebe.

687
00:53:34,645 --> 00:53:39,014
Well, a Kraut by any other name,
uh, Stainsey?

688
00:53:40,918 --> 00:53:45,288
The whole point of
the doomsday machine...

689
00:53:45,357 --> 00:53:48,919
is lost if you keep it a secret!

690
00:53:48,995 --> 00:53:51,156
Why didn't you tell the world?

691
00:53:51,230 --> 00:53:55,633
It was to be announced
at the Party Congress on Monday.

692
00:53:55,703 --> 00:53:59,036
As you know,
the premier loves surprises.

693
00:54:47,528 --> 00:54:49,758
Stay with me, Mandrake.

694
00:54:54,936 --> 00:54:57,632
All right, now feed me.
Feed me, boy.

695
00:55:27,506 --> 00:55:32,570
Don't you think we'd be better off
away from this flying glass?

696
00:55:32,646 --> 00:55:34,705
We're okay here.

697
00:55:36,350 --> 00:55:40,377
Mandrake, do you realize that
in addition to fluoridating the water...

698
00:55:40,455 --> 00:55:44,017
there are studies underway
to fluoridate salt, flour...

699
00:55:44,093 --> 00:55:49,121
fruit juices, soup, sugar,
milk, ice cream?

700
00:55:49,198 --> 00:55:50,461
Ice cream.

701
00:55:50,533 --> 00:55:52,967
- Children's ice cream.
- Good Lord.

702
00:55:53,036 --> 00:55:55,470
You know when fluoridation
first began?

703
00:55:56,506 --> 00:55:58,441
No, I don't, Jack.

